s://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60323"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of enlarged, tender lymph nodes in his left axilla. He has no fever or systemic symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His parent mentions they recently adopted a kitten, and the boy has multiple scratch marks on his left hand from playing with it. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are several healing scratch marks on his left hand and a 3 cm tender lymph node in his left axilla.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria is the most likely implicated pathogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bartonella henselae","Pasteurella multocida","Francisella tularensis","Toxoplasma gondii","Brucella"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of cat scratch disease: regional lymphadenopathy following a cat scratch, particularly from a kitten. The most common causative organism is \u003Cstrong\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/strong\u003E, a gram-negative bacterium that is transmitted through cat scratches or bites. The disease typically presents with regional lymphadenopathy that develops one to three weeks after inoculation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPasteurella multocida\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly associated with cat and dog bites, but typically causes acute cellulitis and soft tissue infection rather than delayed lymphadenopathy. These infections usually develop within 24 hours of the bite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrancisella tularensis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a similar presentation with lymphadenopathy, but is typically associated with exposure to infected rabbits or ticks rather than cats. The infection is usually more severe and accompanied by systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrucella\u003C/strong\u003E causes brucellosis, which is typically acquired through contact with infected animals (usually cattle, sheep, or goats) or consumption of unpasteurised dairy products. While it can cause lymphadenopathy, the exposure history and clinical presentation would be different.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/strong\u003E is a protozoan parasite that can be transmitted through contact with cat faeces, not scratches. While it can cause lymphadenopathy, the transmission route and typical presentation are different from this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECat scratch disease is usually self-limiting and resolves without specific treatment, though antibiotics may be prescribed in severe cases or in immunocompromised patients. The lymphadenopathy typically resolves over two to four months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cat scratch disease is typically caused by Bartonella henselae transmitted through cat scratches or bites.","Regional lymphadenopathy is the hallmark presentation of cat scratch disease.","Young age and contact with cats, especially kittens, are important epidemiological factors in cat scratch disease."],"references":["Raoult D. From Cat scratch disease to Bartonella henselae infection. Clin Infect Dis. 2007;45(12):1541-1542. doi:10.1086/523716"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15150"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T21:36:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T21:37:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7838"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60323"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"